Cut the @Echalion shallot{1} in half through the root, peel and then slice into very 
thin half moon shapes. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a 
#garlic press{} if you have one). Cut each @button mushrooms{1} in half and then 
thinly slice the @portobello mushrooms{2}. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}. 
Keep these ingredients to one side.

Crack the @cardamom pod{6} by whacking them with a #saucepan{}. Tip: You only want 
to break the outer shell and release the seeds inside. Pop them into a 
#pot{} with half of the @vegetable stock pot{1}. Add the @water{350%ml} and then 
put the pot on high heat. Stir to dissolve the stock pot.

Heat a large #frying pan{} on high heat and add a splash of @oil{2%tbsp}. When 
the oil is hot, add your button mushrooms and cook for ~{5%minutes}, stirring 
frequently until browned. When your button mushrooms have browned, transfer them 
to a #bowl{} and add a another splash of @oil{1%tbsp} to the pan. Add your 
portobello mushroom and cook for ~{5%minutes}, stirring frequently until browned.

When your stock is boiling, add the @basmati rice{175%g} and put a lid on the 
pot. Lower the heat until your rice is simmering gently and leave to cook for 
~{10%minutes}. After 10 mins, remove the pot from the heat (keep the lid on) and 
leave your rice to finish cooking in its own steam for another ~{10%minutes}.

When your portobello mushrooms have browned, add your shallot to the pan and 
cook for another ~{3%minutes} or until softened. Return your button mushrooms 
to the pan along with your garlic and @mild paprika{1/2%tsp}. Cook for 
~{1%minute} more and then add the remaining stock pot. Add 4 tbsp of water per 
person and bring to the boil.

Cook for another minute, reduce the heat to low and then stir in the 
@baby spinach{1}. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of 
@black pepper{grind} and then cook until your spinach has wilted completely. 
Remove your sauce from the heat.

Finish your dish by stirring in half the @sour cream{1} and all of your parsley. 
Taste your sauce again and add more salt and pepper if you feel it needs it. Your 
stroganoff is now ready!

Remove your cardamom pods from your rice and then fluff it up with a #fork{}. Serve 
your mushroom stroganoff on top of a bed of rice and finish with a drizzle of 
leftover sour cream.

> The original stroganoff was named after Count Pavel Stroganoff, a noted 19th 
> century Russian diplomat and military commander. He lived in Paris but 
> longed for the food of his homeland, so instructed his private chef to create a 
> French-Russian fusion dish ... and the stroganoff was born!